3. Sunburst Plot

Which categories have more high-discount items? Which discount ranges contribute most to out-of-stock issues?
In[56]:
# Create discount bucket
zep['discount_bucket'] = pd.cut(zep['discountpercent'], bins=[0, 10, 20, 30, 50, 100],
                                labels=['0-10%', '11-20%', '21-30%', '31-50%', '51%+'])

# Convert outofstock to readable label
zep['stock_status'] = zep['outofstock'].map({False: 'In Stock', True: 'Out of Stock'})

# Drop rows with missing path components
sunburst_zep = zep.dropna(subset=['category', 'discount_bucket', 'stock_status'])

# Create Sunburst Plot
fig = px.sunburst(sunburst_zep,
                  path=['category', 'discount_bucket', 'stock_status'],
                  values='availablequantity',
                  color='discount_bucket',
                  title="Sunburst: Category  Discount  Stock Status",
                  height=600)
fig.show()

Word counter- Most Frequent Product Name

In[83]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from collections import Counter
import re

# Safely combine all text columns
text_cols = zep.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
full_text = " ".join(zep[text_cols].fillna('').astype(str).values.ravel())

# Extract words and clean
words = re.findall(r"[A-Za-z]+", full_text.lower())

# Count frequencies
word_counts = Counter(words)

# Optional: remove common filler words
stopwords = {"and","the","for","with","in","of","on","to","a"}
filtered_counts = {w:c for w,c in word_counts.items() if w not in stopwords}

# Get top 20 sorted
top20 = Counter(filtered_counts).most_common(20)

# Convert to DataFrame for plotting
df = pd.DataFrame(top20, columns=['word', 'count'])

# Plot (horizontal bar chart = best for ranking)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.barh(df['word'], df['count'])
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Highest frequency at the top
plt.xlabel("Frequency")
plt.title("Top 20 Most Frequent Words (Ranked High  Low)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

SUMMARY

Insights About Zepto from This Dataset 1.Product Variety: Zepto has a strong focus on essential categories like groceries, dairy, and packaged food, as shown by high product counts in these segments. 2.Pricing Strategy: Significant discounts are applied on many items, especially in certain categories, suggesting a competitive or volume-driven pricing model. 3.Stock Management: While most items are in stock, the presence of out-of-stock items in some categories could reflect demand-supply mismatches. 4.Category Prioritization: Categories like Fruits & Vegetables and Cooking Essentials dominate in variety, indicating core business strengths. 5.Value Proposition: The combination of aggressive discounts and product spread suggests Zepto is targeting both value-seeking and convenience-driven customers. This analysis can help Zepto optimize inventory, pricing, and category focus while improving customer satisfaction.
